Anonymous Sun 07 Aug 2022 16:36:08 No.49958892 Report
Quoted By:
>>49957686
Depends on the setting and what you want to do. A lot of people are used to humanity as the average, and it's easy to write for. So that's a perfectly acceptable starting point when the difference between humans and other species is just never going to be a big issue. Star Trek is a good example of when this does and doesn't work. Most aliens would just be humans with quirks, and they were used to discuss very human problems. But when there were inhuman aliens, they were very unhuman, and their difference from humanity is they key point of nearly all interaction with them.

If there's no point I'd want to make, I'd probably stick to the stuff that most people into science fiction know these days: Compared to other Earth animals humans have great endurance, above average durability, and an uncanny ability to throw things. Physically we're built for running, throwing, and tool use.

In my opinion, the more you invest in these differences, the more central they should be to the setting and story. Humans as space Orcs (or Orks, if you will) is fun, but it falls flat if you don't delve into the why of it and how it affects the narrative. A lot of stories I've seen roll out of HFY just amount to "human fight good", and that's not interesting in itself. Especially when you consider the core of the entire message was to appreciate humanity's quirks as they actually exist compared to other Earth life.

Anonymous Sun 07 Aug 2022 17:38:15 No.49960258 Report
Quoted By: >>49960998 >>49972110
>>49957686
Honestly execution of the setting matters more than any particular element. Don't bait me into thinking this is some hard sci-fi story and then throw space vampires and magical girls at me in the second act, that sort of thing. Consistently applying the rules of the setting is one of the harder things for amateur writers. A lot of them get themselves in trouble by using some hand wave explanation to get out of a particular problem and then don't think about how that hand wave completely undermines the rules of the system they've set up.

Star Trek, even classic Trek, is the worst about this. Often times they deliberately set up a limitation in the first half of the show just to solve it with bullshit in the second half. It's a quick way to write and solve problems, but it makes the world feel entirely plastic because the audience grows to expect all of the rules are up for grabs to make a plot, or have to be completely ignored to keep another plot going.

I think the real difference between sci-fi and fantasy is that good sci-fi tries to build a world like our own but with new constraints via technology, and it explores conflicts within that setting. Flippantly undermining the constraints undermines the story. Whereas fantasy always has an element of building a mysterious world. There's always something deeper and unknown about good fantasy and that's where magic and myth can drive a story without feeling like "it was made up for the plot".
